# {{ PROJECT_NAME }} — chapkit service

{{ PROJECT_DESCRIPTION }}.

This project is now a [**chapkit**](https://github.com/dhis2-chap/chapkit) service — a small FastAPI app that wraps your existing train/predict scripts and exposes them to the [chap-core](https://github.com/dhis2-chap/chap-core) orchestrator as a standard HTTP service.

[`chapkit migrate`](https://dhis2-chap.github.io/chapkit/guides/mlproject-migrate/) generated the wrapper; your scripts are untouched. The original `MLproject` and anything chapkit regenerated (README, pyproject, etc.) are preserved under `_old/`.

## TL;DR

| Do this | You get |
| --- | --- |
| [`uv sync && uv run python main.py`](#run-it-locally) | Service on http://127.0.0.1:8000 |
| [`docker build -t {{ PROJECT_SLUG }} .`](#run-it-in-docker) | Image built on [`{{ BASE_IMAGE }}`](https://github.com/dhis2-chap/chapkit-images) |
| [`chapkit test`](https://dhis2-chap.github.io/chapkit/guides/testing-ml-services/) | End-to-end train + predict smoke test |
| [`/docs`](http://127.0.0.1:8000/docs) | Live OpenAPI UI for the service |

## Run it locally

```bash
uv sync                # installs chapkit + your deps into .venv
uv run python main.py   # serves on http://127.0.0.1:8000
```

Poke at [http://127.0.0.1:8000/docs](http://127.0.0.1:8000/docs) for the OpenAPI UI, or `/health` for a heartbeat.

## Run it in Docker

```bash
docker build -t {{ PROJECT_SLUG }} .
docker run --rm -p 8000:8000 {{ PROJECT_SLUG }}
```

The image builds on [`ghcr.io/dhis2-chap/{{ BASE_IMAGE }}:latest`](https://github.com/dhis2-chap/chapkit-images), one of the pre-baked [chapkit base images](https://github.com/dhis2-chap/chapkit-images) with Python/R and the common ML stack ready to go.
{% if BASE_IMAGE == "chapkit-r-inla" %}
> **Note:** `chapkit-r-inla` is `amd64`-only (INLA ships only x86_64 binaries). On Apple Silicon add `--platform=linux/amd64` to both `docker build` and `docker run`.
{% endif %}

## Smoke-test the service

[`chapkit test`](https://dhis2-chap.github.io/chapkit/guides/testing-ml-services/) POSTs a synthetic config, drives a full train → predict cycle, and reports back. Useful right after migrating to confirm the wiring is sound.

```bash
# terminal 1:
uv run python main.py

# terminal 2:
uv run chapkit test
```

The generator produces [chap-core-shaped panel data](https://dhis2-chap.github.io/chapkit/guides/testing-ml-services/#generated-data-structure) (`time_period`, `location`, `disease_cases`, `population`, `rainfall`, `mean_temperature`, plus any [`required_covariates`](#covariates) your model declares).

## What's in the box

- **`main.py`** — the generated chapkit service. Defines your [`{{ PROJECT_CLASS_NAME }}Config`](https://dhis2-chap.github.io/chapkit/guides/configuration-management/), wires a [`ShellModelRunner`](https://dhis2-chap.github.io/chapkit/guides/ml-workflows/#shellmodelrunner) to your scripts, and hands everything to [`MLServiceBuilder`](https://dhis2-chap.github.io/chapkit/guides/ml-workflows/#mlservicebuilder-recommended).
- **`Dockerfile`**, **`compose.yml`**, **`pyproject.toml`**, **`postman_collection.json`**, **`README.md`**, **`.gitignore`**, **`.dockerignore`** — all generated, all yours to edit.
- **Your train/predict scripts**, helpers, Python packages, lockfiles, `LICENSE`, and any arbitrary `*.yaml`/`*.json` config files your scripts read — **untouched**, at the project root.
- **`_old/`** — safety net: original `MLproject`, pre-existing metadata files chapkit regenerated, example input/output, ad-hoc runners (`isolated_run.*`). Nothing here is loaded at runtime; browse freely, copy anything worth porting back.
{% if HAS_USER_PYPROJECT %}

### Dependencies from your original `pyproject.toml`

Your runtime deps (`[project.dependencies]`) have been auto-merged into the new `pyproject.toml` alongside the `chapkit` entry. The original file is at `_old/pyproject.toml` — check it for anything we didn't port automatically: optional dep groups, `[tool.ruff]`/`[tool.mypy]` config, environment markers, custom `[build-system]` backends.
{% endif %}

## Key concepts (all generated into `main.py`)

### [`MLServiceInfo`](https://dhis2-chap.github.io/chapkit/guides/ml-workflows/#mlserviceinfo-fields) — who you are

The service's public identity and contract: `id`, `display_name`, `description`, [`model_metadata`](https://dhis2-chap.github.io/chapkit/guides/ml-workflows/#modelmetadata-fields), [`period_type`](https://dhis2-chap.github.io/chapkit/guides/ml-workflows/#mlserviceinfo-fields) (`monthly` / `weekly`), [`required_covariates`](#covariates). This is what chap-core reads via `/api/v1/info` when it decides whether to dispatch a dataset to your model.

### [`ModelMetadata.author_assessed_status`](https://dhis2-chap.github.io/chapkit/guides/ml-workflows/#modelmetadata-fields) — traffic-light maturity

One of `green` / `yellow` / `orange` / `red` / `gray`. Self-assessed by you, the model author; visible to anyone browsing chap-core. Rough semantics:

| Status | Meaning |
| --- | --- |
| `green` | Validated, recommended for production use |
| `yellow` | Works, but results should be reviewed |
| `orange` | Experimental; correctness not guaranteed |
| `red` | Known issues; don't use in production |
| `gray` | Not yet assessed |

Migrate defaults to `yellow` when the MLproject doesn't set one — bump it up (or down) to match reality.

### [`{{ PROJECT_CLASS_NAME }}Config`](https://dhis2-chap.github.io/chapkit/guides/configuration-management/) — your tunable knobs

A [`BaseConfig`](https://dhis2-chap.github.io/chapkit/api-reference/#chapkit.config.schemas.BaseConfig) subclass with typed fields derived from your MLproject's `user_options`. Each POSTed config becomes a row in the service's DB and feeds into train/predict via `config.yml` (see [`config.yml` layout](#configyml-layout)).

### [`ShellModelRunner`](https://dhis2-chap.github.io/chapkit/guides/ml-workflows/#shellmodelrunner) — runs your scripts

Wraps `train_command` / `predict_command`. For each train or predict job chapkit copies your project into a temp workspace, writes `data.csv` / `historic.csv` / `future.csv` / `config.yml` / `geo.json`, runs your script there, and captures the whole workspace as an [artifact](#artifacts).

### [`ArtifactHierarchy`](https://dhis2-chap.github.io/chapkit/guides/artifact-storage/) — keeps your runs

Every train and predict call produces an [artifact](https://dhis2-chap.github.io/chapkit/guides/artifact-storage/) (a zipped workspace with logs, the trained model, predictions, etc.). They're linked parent-child so you can trace a prediction back to the training run that produced it.

## `config.yml` layout

Your scripts receive a `config.yml` in the working directory on every train/predict call. The generated `main.py` picks `config_format="chap_core"` so the file matches [chap-core's `ModelConfiguration` shape](https://github.com/dhis2-chap/chap-core/blob/master/chap_core/database/model_templates_and_config_tables.py):

```yaml
prediction_periods: 3
additional_continuous_covariates: [rainfall, mean_temperature]
user_option_values:
  n_lags: 3
  precision: 0.01
```

- `prediction_periods` and `additional_continuous_covariates` are **reserved** — always at the top level.
- Anything else you put on the Config class nests under `user_option_values`.

That's the shape scripts ported from the `chap-models` ecosystem already expect — they read `config["user_option_values"]["<option>"]` (Python) or `config$user_option_values$<option>` (R) unchanged.

**Prefer flat?** Switch `config_format="flat"` in `main.py` and keys land at the top level — good fit when you own the scripts and don't need chap-core compatibility. This is the default for [`chapkit init`](https://dhis2-chap.github.io/chapkit/guides/cli-scaffolding/) scaffolds.

## Covariates

Two fields, two different jobs:

| Field | Lives on | When to use |
| --- | --- | --- |
| [`MLServiceInfo.required_covariates`](https://dhis2-chap.github.io/chapkit/guides/ml-workflows/#mlserviceinfo-fields) | The service | The model cannot function without these columns. chap-core refuses to dispatch if they're missing. Use when your scripts hardcode feature names. |
| [`{{ PROJECT_CLASS_NAME }}Config.additional_continuous_covariates`](https://dhis2-chap.github.io/chapkit/guides/configuration-management/) | Per config | Extra climate covariates to lag as predictors. Set per-deployment via a POSTed config; the default in `main.py` is the fallback. |

When in doubt, **prefer `required_covariates`** — it's the stricter contract and the one chap-core checks at dispatch time.

## Artifacts

Each train/predict call leaves a zipped workspace behind, browsable at [`/api/v1/artifacts`](http://127.0.0.1:8000/docs#/artifacts). Jobs are scheduled via [`/api/v1/jobs`](http://127.0.0.1:8000/docs#/jobs) so you can POST training and poll for completion. Full API reference: [`/docs`](http://127.0.0.1:8000/docs) once the service is running, or the [ML workflows guide](https://dhis2-chap.github.io/chapkit/guides/ml-workflows/#api-reference).

## Registering with chap-core

The generated `main.py` calls `.with_registration()`, so when the service starts with `SERVICEKIT_ORCHESTRATOR_URL` set, it auto-registers with chap-core and sends keepalive pings. No env var → silently no-ops, so local `python main.py` just runs the service.

```yaml
# compose fragment
services:
  {{ PROJECT_SLUG }}:
    build: .
{% if BASE_IMAGE == "chapkit-r-inla" %}
    platform: linux/amd64
{% endif %}
    environment:
      SERVICEKIT_ORCHESTRATOR_URL: http://chap:8000/v2/services/$$register
      # SERVICEKIT_REGISTRATION_KEY: ${SERVICEKIT_REGISTRATION_KEY:-}   # optional shared secret
    depends_on:
      chap:
        condition: service_healthy
```

